o groups slowly accepted him as an investigatoractivist and later expelled him for his ideologically uncommitted stance and refusal to subject his observations to censorship. His activities as a fascist were often mundane: leafleting, distributing food parcels to the indigent, and attending public rallies. In Sacrifice, Orsini describes from within the masculine ethos of the militias, the groups' relations with local police and politicians, and the central role of violence and anticommunist actions in building a sense of fascist community.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aEthnologyxItalyxItaly. 0aEthnologyzItaly. 0aFascismx1945-xItaly. 0aFascismzItalyy1945- 0aFascismzItalyy1945-. 0aFascistsxSocial conditionsx21st centuryxItaly. 0aFascistszItalyxSocial conditionsy21st century. 0aMilitia movementsxHistoryx21st centuryxItaly. 0aMilitia movementszItalyxHistoryy21st century. 4aEurope. 4aItaly. 4aSociology & Social Science. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Italy.2bisacsh1 aNodes, Sarah J.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066587140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501709630zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501709630423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501709630.jpg  a978-3-11-066587-1  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles